## Use straight/ASCII punctuation only -- no smart/curly characters

This rule exists because smart punctuation causes StrReplace and other tool calls to silently fail when the characters in the tool call do not exactly match the bytes on disk.

### Quotes
- **Never** use curly double quotes: `"` (U+201C) or `"` (U+201D). Use `"` (U+0022) only.
- **Never** use curly single quotes or smart apostrophes: `'` (U+2018), `'` (U+2019). Use `'` (U+0027) only.

### Dashes
- **Never** use an em dash `--` (U+2014) or en dash `-` (U+2013). Use a double hyphen `--` or a spaced hyphen ` - ` instead.

### Ellipsis
- **Never** use the ellipsis character `...` (U+2026). Use three plain dots `...` instead.

### Applies everywhere
- Markdown files, code comments, string literals, copy -- everywhere.
- When writing `old_string` in a StrReplace call, reproduce the exact bytes from the file. If the file contains smart punctuation (written before this rule was in place), copy those exact characters into `old_string` rather than retyping them.
